SECTION A

1. Multiple choice answers with explanations:

(i) C. the Earth’s surfaces and the relationship between people and environment — Geography studies people‑environment interactions. :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}

(ii) B. lithosphere — The lithosphere consists of the crust and upper mantle. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

(iii) B. short‑term atmospheric conditions — Weather is the day‑to‑day state of the atmosphere. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

(iv) C. elevation and relief features — Topographic maps use contour lines to show physical terrain. :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}

(v) C. elevation and slope — Contour lines connect points of equal elevation, showing slope steepness. :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}

(vi) B. Deforestation — Removing trees affects water infiltration and runoff. :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}

(vii) A. demography — Demography is the study of population characteristics. :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}

(viii) B. extracting minerals while ensuring environmental protection and future use — Sustainable mining balances use and conservation. :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}

(ix) B. Rivers — Rivers provide water for hydroelectric power. :contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}

(x) B. distance between two places — Map scale helps convert map distances to real‑world distances. :contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}

2. Matching:

(i) B — Climate: long‑term atmospheric conditions. :contentReference[oaicite:11]{index=11}
(ii) A — Photograph interpretation uses aerial views to analyse landscapes. :contentReference[oaicite:12]{index=12}
(iii) E — Settlement patterns study how people live and organise places. :contentReference[oaicite:13]{index=13}
(iv) C — Soil conservation preserves soil and prevents erosion. :contentReference[oaicite:14]{index=14}
(v) D — Transport systems facilitate movement of goods and people. :contentReference[oaicite:15]{index=15}
(vi) F — Research in geography uses systematic investigation to answer questions. :contentReference[oaicite:16]{index=16}

SECTION B

3. (a) Geography is the study of the Earth’s surfaces and the interactions between people and their environment. Major branches include Physical Geography (studies natural features such as landforms, climate, soils) and Human Geography (studies human activities, population, settlement). :contentReference[oaicite:17]{index=17}

(b) Geography helps in planning land use, managing natural resources, understanding weather patterns for agriculture, and solving human‑environment problems in daily life. :contentReference[oaicite:18]{index=18}

4. (a) Relief features are shown using contour lines on topographic maps; close spacing indicates steep slopes, wide spacing indicates gentle slopes. :contentReference[oaicite:19]{index=19}

(b) Limitations of contour lines: they may be difficult to interpret for beginners; they cannot show underground features. :contentReference[oaicite:20]{index=20}

5. (a) Weather refers to short‑term atmospheric conditions; climate is the average weather over a long period (usually 30 years). :contentReference[oaicite:21]{index=21}

(b) Factors that influence climate include latitude (distance from equator) and altitude (higher altitudes are cooler). :contentReference[oaicite:22]{index=22}

6. (a) Population distribution is the pattern of where people live across an area. :contentReference[oaicite:23]{index=23}

(b) Uneven distribution may be caused by physical factors (such as rugged terrain) and economic factors (such as availability of jobs). :contentReference[oaicite:24]{index=24}

7. (a) Water resources are essential for domestic use, agriculture (irrigation), industry, and generation of hydroelectric power. :contentReference[oaicite:25]{index=25}

(b) Human activities like pollution and over‑abstraction (excessive withdrawal) can degrade water quality and reduce availability. :contentReference[oaicite:26]{index=26}

8. (a) Sustainable use of forest resources means using forests in ways that meet present needs without harming future availability. :contentReference[oaicite:27]{index=27}

(b) Strategies include reforestation (planting trees) and enforcing logging regulations to reduce over‑exploitation. :contentReference[oaicite:28]{index=28}

SECTION C

9. (a) Conducting field survey: select area, measure distances using tape and compass, record features, draw base map; instruments include compass, tape measure, clinometer. :contentReference[oaicite:29]{index=29}

   (b) Statistics in research: collecting numerical data, calculating averages, using graphs and tables to interpret patterns. :contentReference[oaicite:30]{index=30}

10. (a) Factors influencing agriculture: climate (rainfall and temperature), soil types, availability of water for irrigation. :contentReference[oaicite:31]{index=31}

    (b) Transportation contributes to economic development by linking producers to markets, reducing cost of goods and facilitating trade. :contentReference[oaicite:32]{index=32}

11. (a) Causes of soil erosion: deforestation removes protective cover; overgrazing exposes soil to erosion. :contentReference[oaicite:33]{index=33}

    (b) Soil erosion can be controlled by terracing on slopes and planting cover crops to protect soil. :contentReference[oaicite:34]{index=34}

End of Answers.

HAnswers.content:
SECTION A

1. (a) Multiple choice answers with explanations:

(i) B. Oral traditions — Oral traditions include stories and narrations passed from generation to generation, providing direct community recollections of the past. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

(ii) C. Africa — Early human remains and evidence of early humans (hominids) have been discovered in Africa, making it the cradle of humankind. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

(iii) C. It regulated European colonization of Africa — The Berlin Conference formalised the rules for European powers to partition Africa, leading to colonial rule. :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}

(iv) A. Industrial revolution — The need for raw materials and markets during the Industrial Revolution drove European expansion into Africa. :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}

(v) B. Desire for independence from colonial rule — Nationalism refers to efforts by Africans to end colonial domination and gain self‑rule. :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}

(vi) C. South Africa — Apartheid was a system of racial segregation implemented in South Africa. :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}

(vii) B. OAU — The Organisation of African Unity was established to promote solidarity among African states. :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}

(viii) C. Kwame Nkrumah — Nkrumah led Ghana to independence from British rule in 1957. :contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}

(ix) B. Development of cash crop economy — Colonial economic policies prioritised cash crops for export, shaping post‑colonial economies. :contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}

(x) D. All of the above — Many African states faced political, social, and economic challenges after independence. :contentReference[oaicite:11]{index=11}

1. (b) Matching:
(i) C — Pre‑colonial African economy existed before European domination. :contentReference[oaicite:12]{index=12}
(ii) D — Colonial administrative system refers to systems of governance under colonial powers. :contentReference[oaicite:13]{index=13}
(iii) B — Atlantic slave trade forced millions of Africans into slavery. :contentReference[oaicite:14]{index=14}
(iv) E — Decolonization was the struggle for independence from colonial rule. :contentReference[oaicite:15]{index=15}
(v) A — Pan‑Africanism is the ideology advocating African unity. :contentReference[oaicite:16]{index=16}

SECTION B

2.
(a) History is the study of past events and human experiences over time. (Include reasons such as understanding the past to make informed decisions today, learning about cultural heritage.)
(b) Two reasons: to understand how societies change over time; to learn from past successes and failures.

3.
(a) Oral traditions preserve cultural practices, beliefs, and experiences of ancestors that are not recorded in written form.
(b) Limitation: They may change over time and be influenced by memory biases.

4.
(a) Two economic effects: introduction of cash crop farming that reduced subsistence agriculture; exploitation of resources for colonial benefits.
(b) Colonial education often aimed at producing clerks and labourers to serve colonial administration, creating limited access to quality education.

5.
(a) Causes of the scramble for Africa: Industrial revolution’s need for raw materials; European competition for global power; strategic locations for trade and military advantage.
(b) One consequence: artificial borders drawn at the Berlin Conference caused ethnic divisions and future conflicts.

SECTION C

6.
(a) Origins and development of nationalism in Ghana: Nationalist movements grew out of dissatisfaction with colonial rule, formation of groups like UGCC and CPP.
(b) Nationalism contributed to independence by mobilising mass support, strikes, boycotts and negotiation which led Britain to grant independence in 1957.

7.
(a) First World War exposed African soldiers to ideas of self‑determination; colonial powers weakened financially.
(b) Returning ex‑soldiers demanded rights and equality, inspiring nationalist movements.

8.
(a) OAU promoted unity by encouraging cooperation among African states and resisting colonial rule.
(b) Successes: helped end colonial rule in some states; Limitations: internal conflicts and lack of enforcement power.

9.
(a) Causes of political instability: ethnic rivalries, weak institutions, military coups.
(b) Measures to promote stability: strengthen democratic institutions; promote national unity education.
